1
00:00:06,400 --> 00:00:08,961
Hi, I'm Guha Bala, president of Valance Studios.

2
00:00:09,501 --> 00:00:12,942
I'm Kartek Bala, Guha's brother, CEO of Valance Studios.

3
00:00:12,962 --> 00:00:16,544
You know, previously we were founders of Vicarious Visions,

4
00:00:17,284 --> 00:00:21,145
which we started when we were both in high school back in 1991 in our parents' basement.

5
00:00:21,706 --> 00:00:24,027
Now, Vivi became part of Activision Blizzard in 2005.

6
00:00:24,087 --> 00:00:27,988
We led the studio for 25 years and worked on some good games.

7
00:00:28,588 --> 00:00:31,890
And then we set out on a new adventure to become entrepreneurs again.

8
00:00:32,735 --> 00:00:34,937
We founded Vellum Studios in 2016

9
00:00:35,037 --> 00:00:37,439
to build a studio focused on discovery.

10
00:00:38,320 --> 00:00:40,782
Our desire is to build a sustainable studio

11
00:00:40,822 --> 00:00:42,583
with creative and financial independence

12
00:00:42,663 --> 00:00:44,685
where industry veteran teams

13
00:00:45,045 --> 00:00:46,767
could take the sort of creative risks

14
00:00:47,367 --> 00:00:49,429
and create new kinds of game experiences.

15
00:00:50,290 --> 00:00:52,431
We're a studio of around 90 employees right now

16
00:00:52,912 --> 00:00:54,353
based in Troy, New York.

17
00:00:55,234 --> 00:00:59,837
And simply put, our mission is to create breakthrough games

18
00:00:59,877 --> 00:01:00,438
that are magical.

19
00:01:02,243 --> 00:01:06,527
Our first couple of games, you know, first one we launched last fall, super proud of it,

20
00:01:06,907 --> 00:01:11,471
Mario Kart Live Home Circuit, released October 2020 in partnership with Nintendo.

21
00:01:12,271 --> 00:01:17,375
Now that's a mixed reality video game that brings the Mario Kart experience into the real world

22
00:01:17,776 --> 00:01:25,022
by merging an AR camera-enabled RC kart and a video game world into one. It was a prototype

23
00:01:25,142 --> 00:01:31,667
that was invented at Valon and then developed into a fully realized game in partnership with Nintendo.

24
00:01:33,188 --> 00:01:36,069
and just announced recently is Knockout City,

25
00:01:36,670 --> 00:01:39,832
a new kind of online multiplayer team-based action game

26
00:01:40,312 --> 00:01:42,193
in partnership with EA Originals.

27
00:01:43,113 --> 00:01:45,595
The core mechanic is based on the simple premise

28
00:01:45,855 --> 00:01:47,516
of throwing and catching a ball

29
00:01:48,036 --> 00:01:51,398
and amplified into a dodge-crawling online game.

30
00:01:52,499 --> 00:01:54,840
There were so many technical and design challenges

31
00:01:55,300 --> 00:01:58,042
with this title, with latency being a key issue,

32
00:01:58,662 --> 00:02:00,683
that the team had to build a new game engine

33
00:02:01,103 --> 00:02:02,444
from the ground up to pull it off.

34
00:02:03,762 --> 00:02:06,364
Just a quick plug, we've got an upcoming cross-play beta,

35
00:02:06,624 --> 00:02:07,844
April 2nd through the 4th.

36
00:02:08,185 --> 00:02:10,166
We'd love for you to join and check it out.

37
00:02:10,226 --> 00:02:10,966
We think you'll like it.

38
00:02:11,707 --> 00:02:13,207
Now, the game will be coming out in May

39
00:02:14,188 --> 00:02:16,349
and in partnership with EA Originals.

40
00:02:16,769 --> 00:02:18,590
Now, the games couldn't be more different,

41
00:02:19,711 --> 00:02:24,153
but their path to discovery and creation have a lot in common.

42
00:02:26,375 --> 00:02:30,397
You know, when we talk about the culture of discovery at Velen,

43
00:02:31,958 --> 00:02:32,918
for us, it's essential.

44
00:02:33,496 --> 00:02:36,917
to think about convergent and divergent thinking.

45
00:02:37,757 --> 00:02:39,898
They're starkly different approaches to creativity.

46
00:02:40,939 --> 00:02:43,239
It's not that one is better than the other,

47
00:02:43,559 --> 00:02:44,940
but they serve very different goals.

48
00:02:45,600 --> 00:02:47,501
Now we hear everyone talking about innovation,

49
00:02:47,581 --> 00:02:48,541
but what does that really mean?

50
00:02:49,462 --> 00:02:51,282
Is it making something that exists better

51
00:02:51,302 --> 00:02:53,683
or doing something totally new?

52
00:02:53,703 --> 00:02:57,744
A lot of great developers focus on being the best

53
00:02:57,804 --> 00:02:58,325
in their craft.

54
00:02:58,919 --> 00:03:03,902
Now, this often overlaps with the goal of being best at what exists.

55
00:03:05,083 --> 00:03:09,366
There are existing game genres. There are established game behaviors for consumers.

56
00:03:10,126 --> 00:03:13,569
It's easy to understand when described, or you pitch, or you show a trailer.

57
00:03:14,649 --> 00:03:16,331
And craftsmanship is key.

58
00:03:18,992 --> 00:03:22,675
And these are examples of convergent thinking where you're best in class.

59
00:03:22,735 --> 00:03:25,477
You know, most franchise extensions are based on this.

60
00:03:26,682 --> 00:03:30,284
easier to plan for, communicate, fund, and publish.

61
00:03:31,826 --> 00:03:36,709
Then there are developers who focus on something new.

62
00:03:36,809 --> 00:03:40,572
At first, every pitch starts with, hey, this is really new.

63
00:03:41,393 --> 00:03:43,194
But we found that really new ideas

64
00:03:43,234 --> 00:03:44,655
have a few things in common.

65
00:03:45,896 --> 00:03:46,917
Uniqueness is key.

66
00:03:47,898 --> 00:03:49,159
You feel different when you play.

67
00:03:49,179 --> 00:03:51,821
It has a unique emotional response.

68
00:03:52,201 --> 00:03:54,703
The moment-to-moment interaction is different,

69
00:03:55,363 --> 00:03:56,364
whether it's narrative.

70
00:03:56,879 --> 00:03:58,660
or it's a new kind of Twitch-based mechanic.

71
00:03:58,740 --> 00:04:00,161
It feels different at its core.

72
00:04:00,842 --> 00:04:02,884
It's hard to describe it with just video and text.

73
00:04:02,984 --> 00:04:03,845
Playing is believing.

74
00:04:03,885 --> 00:04:06,006
You've got to get it in a player's hands.

75
00:04:07,988 --> 00:04:15,074
So it's really important overall to make an explicit choice

76
00:04:16,155 --> 00:04:18,557
in which way you want to go, because it

77
00:04:18,577 --> 00:04:21,500
becomes the basis of your culture as a studio

78
00:04:22,140 --> 00:04:22,881
and the business model.

79
00:04:25,644 --> 00:04:27,925
When we decided to be game developers,

80
00:04:28,045 --> 00:04:29,466
as creative people often do,

81
00:04:30,206 --> 00:04:32,247
we often think about the new things

82
00:04:32,328 --> 00:04:34,649
we're setting out to invent, to think differently.

83
00:04:35,749 --> 00:04:36,970
But we quickly discovered

84
00:04:37,050 --> 00:04:39,051
that most of the commercial opportunities

85
00:04:39,551 --> 00:04:42,073
that are out there were built on convergent thinking

86
00:04:42,373 --> 00:04:43,273
rather than divergent.

87
00:04:44,174 --> 00:04:45,234
There's a lot of reasons why.

88
00:04:46,195 --> 00:04:49,116
Convergence is iteration and craftsmanship.

89
00:04:49,897 --> 00:04:53,358
It's the only way to become and stay the best in class

90
00:04:54,071 --> 00:04:55,591
in a very competitive marketplace.

91
00:04:56,631 --> 00:04:58,412
Companies iterate for a variety of reasons.

92
00:04:58,912 --> 00:05:00,812
First, they're committed to their value chains

93
00:05:01,312 --> 00:05:02,253
and their business models.

94
00:05:03,253 --> 00:05:05,833
The value chain is a set of organizational choices

95
00:05:05,853 --> 00:05:08,574
that they've made, people, infrastructure,

96
00:05:09,134 --> 00:05:11,114
management bias, like how you think

97
00:05:12,094 --> 00:05:13,495
about business in the industry.

98
00:05:14,975 --> 00:05:18,296
These things are woven together in a system of activities,

99
00:05:18,356 --> 00:05:20,036
how they're gonna deliver for their customers.

100
00:05:21,876 --> 00:05:23,177
Their business models in particular.

101
00:05:24,413 --> 00:05:26,054
are sort of areas of focus.

102
00:05:26,094 --> 00:05:27,675
They really specialize and differentiate

103
00:05:27,695 --> 00:05:28,535
in their business models.

104
00:05:28,615 --> 00:05:30,636
Some companies are committed to free to play games.

105
00:05:31,517 --> 00:05:33,198
Some are very category specific,

106
00:05:34,538 --> 00:05:36,779
MMOs or MOBAs as the case may be.

107
00:05:37,780 --> 00:05:39,441
And some are premium price publishers.

108
00:05:40,161 --> 00:05:42,402
And no matter what they do to do things differently,

109
00:05:42,842 --> 00:05:43,863
they come from that place.

110
00:05:44,563 --> 00:05:45,964
Each of these companies strategies

111
00:05:46,044 --> 00:05:48,505
are as much a factor of their current resources

112
00:05:49,026 --> 00:05:50,807
and expertise as they are about

113
00:05:50,847 --> 00:05:51,967
where they'd like to be in the future.

114
00:05:53,373 --> 00:05:59,237
Second big reason that companies iterate, all companies need to focus, usually around how

115
00:05:59,257 --> 00:06:06,123
they're currently delivering their cash flows from their customers to their shareholders.

116
00:06:07,143 --> 00:06:13,168
And it sounds really smart to have a complex strategy. The problem is complex ones don't

117
00:06:13,228 --> 00:06:19,533
usually work. Simple strategies with focused execution is what really works. And that's a

118
00:06:19,573 --> 00:06:21,755
lot of the reasons why companies iterate as well.

119
00:06:22,804 --> 00:06:23,725
There's also more reasons.

120
00:06:24,185 --> 00:06:25,906
There's lower market acceptance risk.

121
00:06:26,487 --> 00:06:30,090
When you put all the capital into building a game,

122
00:06:30,390 --> 00:06:33,552
all the costs, the money, the effort, the time,

123
00:06:34,293 --> 00:06:37,295
it's much easier to know, is there anyone out there

124
00:06:37,315 --> 00:06:38,616
that's an audience for your title?

125
00:06:39,176 --> 00:06:41,578
It's easier to focus test and research it,

126
00:06:41,939 --> 00:06:43,680
however formally or informally.

127
00:06:44,721 --> 00:06:46,162
Iteration is much easier to do this.

128
00:06:46,702 --> 00:06:48,564
It's a lot easier to forecast financials.

129
00:06:48,604 --> 00:06:50,085
You can look at similar titles out there.

130
00:06:50,421 --> 00:06:53,182
and say, hey, I can make this a little bit better, a little bit plus 10%.

131
00:06:54,023 --> 00:06:59,466
So the bottom line is, is that it's a lot easier to invest in a bigger bet.

132
00:06:59,866 --> 00:07:04,829
That's even better for customers by giving them more of what they already love.

133
00:07:06,189 --> 00:07:09,771
You know, finally, and this is one thing that's always been a little uncomfortable

134
00:07:09,791 --> 00:07:13,073
for people to admit, it's something that we've gone through as well.

135
00:07:13,093 --> 00:07:15,274
There's a lower chance of failure.

136
00:07:16,835 --> 00:07:18,516
At least until the idea gets old.

137
00:07:19,825 --> 00:07:21,846
There's a lower chance of failure in iterative ideas

138
00:07:21,926 --> 00:07:24,948
because when was the last time someone got promoted

139
00:07:24,988 --> 00:07:26,828
at a company for failing in the marketplace?

140
00:07:28,589 --> 00:07:30,630
Well, typically if you fail in the marketplace,

141
00:07:31,811 --> 00:07:34,953
you blow up and it's a sort of a career limiting move.

142
00:07:36,093 --> 00:07:37,654
So you tend to iterate rather

143
00:07:37,694 --> 00:07:39,175
than do something completely different.

144
00:07:41,496 --> 00:07:43,517
Everyone seems to have the story of the brand

145
00:07:43,537 --> 00:07:46,798
that they helped create as executives in a company.

146
00:07:47,533 --> 00:07:49,734
I was part of X team or Y team.

147
00:07:50,314 --> 00:07:51,415
Usually people don't talk about,

148
00:07:51,435 --> 00:07:54,296
I was part of a team that took a risk and it didn't work out.

149
00:07:55,576 --> 00:07:58,138
And then finally, and this is a big one,

150
00:07:58,158 --> 00:08:00,999
it's a lot easier if you're in a $100 million business

151
00:08:01,039 --> 00:08:04,500
to get the extra 10%, the over $10 million of revenue,

152
00:08:05,221 --> 00:08:06,581
or in a billion dollar business

153
00:08:06,641 --> 00:08:07,802
and get an extra 100 million.

154
00:08:07,842 --> 00:08:09,523
Wow, that sounds really like a big number, right?

155
00:08:10,343 --> 00:08:12,484
Then it is to get to the first 10 million of revenue

156
00:08:12,544 --> 00:08:13,204
on a new idea,

157
00:08:13,764 --> 00:08:17,086
or the first $100 million of a new idea.

158
00:08:18,140 --> 00:08:20,441
And so for someone looking to build a career,

159
00:08:22,282 --> 00:08:24,643
jumping off the deep end with a brand new idea,

160
00:08:25,344 --> 00:08:27,245
it's the reason why creative people sometimes

161
00:08:27,285 --> 00:08:27,945
get in the business.

162
00:08:28,525 --> 00:08:31,727
But it's not the best path for the most predictable career.

163
00:08:32,548 --> 00:08:36,129
Frankly, if all creative companies was divergent

164
00:08:36,169 --> 00:08:39,231
thinking, and so everybody in the world

165
00:08:39,271 --> 00:08:41,752
was doing things differently, then eventually, luck

166
00:08:41,772 --> 00:08:42,393
might run out.

167
00:08:43,393 --> 00:08:45,194
Even the most divergent of innovators

168
00:08:45,334 --> 00:08:47,335
need some convergence and iteration.

169
00:08:49,112 --> 00:08:52,854
But of course, the same old, same old, as we say, gets old.

170
00:08:55,575 --> 00:08:59,298
There's always room for something new, especially now.

171
00:09:00,058 --> 00:09:03,080
Now, that's a lot of the reasons why we got into balance studios

172
00:09:03,120 --> 00:09:05,921
and started our studio in the first place.

173
00:09:07,602 --> 00:09:10,023
But especially now, it's a good time to recognize

174
00:09:10,084 --> 00:09:12,445
that the industry is very cyclical.

175
00:09:13,545 --> 00:09:16,607
It's always in a process of consolidation and fragmentation.

176
00:09:17,058 --> 00:09:21,160
And they're always breakthrough new products coming supposedly out of nowhere.

177
00:09:21,580 --> 00:09:25,061
Usually it's a team that worked for ten years to get the right idea going,

178
00:09:25,521 --> 00:09:26,561
been incubating forever.

179
00:09:26,581 --> 00:09:28,582
And supposedly all the new ideas come out of nowhere.

180
00:09:29,922 --> 00:09:35,064
Established game categories are getting bigger, that's a truism.

181
00:09:35,084 --> 00:09:36,564
That's where the consolidation is happening.

182
00:09:36,704 --> 00:09:39,985
Only the top few MOBAs are getting the consumers today,

183
00:09:40,005 --> 00:09:43,146
the top few Battle Royales, the top few match three games.

184
00:09:44,526 --> 00:09:46,867
And they have staying power because they can invest at scale.

185
00:09:49,573 --> 00:09:55,254
And before that, before today, or now,

186
00:09:55,814 --> 00:10:00,495
big publishers controlled access to capital, distribution, marketing, and PR.

187
00:10:02,496 --> 00:10:03,496
But at the same time,

188
00:10:03,676 --> 00:10:07,457
we've never experienced a time where each of these areas are more disaggregated.

189
00:10:07,817 --> 00:10:13,078
When it comes to new types of experiences, there's always new capital or

190
00:10:13,178 --> 00:10:14,758
always capital chasing new creatives.

191
00:10:16,188 --> 00:10:17,669
The different distribution options,

192
00:10:17,709 --> 00:10:19,930
virtually for any business model.

193
00:10:20,930 --> 00:10:22,671
And there's world-class marketing PR

194
00:10:23,551 --> 00:10:26,393
that's looking to support the best new creative.

195
00:10:27,213 --> 00:10:30,574
So we frankly don't see many advantages

196
00:10:30,614 --> 00:10:32,575
of being within a single large organization,

197
00:10:32,595 --> 00:10:36,517
especially if you wanna get something done that's new.

198
00:10:37,917 --> 00:10:40,958
There are multiple routes for unique experiences

199
00:10:41,419 --> 00:10:42,899
if you're deliberate in your choices.

200
00:10:43,579 --> 00:10:43,940
It's not.

201
00:10:44,936 --> 00:10:47,677
It's not actually the field of dreams where build it and they will come.

202
00:10:48,158 --> 00:10:51,159
It does take a few very deliberate steps.

203
00:10:53,100 --> 00:10:56,302
We'll talk about our perspective on doing divergence.

204
00:10:58,143 --> 00:11:02,445
The key is for us to build ideas that are simple.

205
00:11:03,986 --> 00:11:09,069
By simple, we mean sort of really easy to get, easy to understand, accessible.

206
00:11:09,089 --> 00:11:10,830
It's easy to get into and start playing.

207
00:11:11,950 --> 00:11:14,412
It's something that is emotional or captivating.

208
00:11:14,920 --> 00:11:16,301
within the first few minutes of play.

209
00:11:16,521 --> 00:11:18,002
It doesn't take a long exposition,

210
00:11:18,022 --> 00:11:22,925
a long sort of experience to really understand what it is

211
00:11:23,105 --> 00:11:24,566
and say, ah, this feels different.

212
00:11:25,607 --> 00:11:27,288
But simple doesn't mean it's complex under,

213
00:11:27,428 --> 00:11:28,849
it's not complex under the hood.

214
00:11:28,869 --> 00:11:31,351
A lot of times simple ideas haven't been done before

215
00:11:31,371 --> 00:11:32,431
because they're super hard to do.

216
00:11:33,632 --> 00:11:35,173
Second principle, defensible.

217
00:11:36,354 --> 00:11:38,735
Is there a secret sauce that makes this hard to copy?

218
00:11:39,576 --> 00:11:41,177
You know, I remember when the first couple

219
00:11:42,238 --> 00:11:44,199
Battle Royals came out and we went to that.

220
00:11:45,473 --> 00:11:49,255
E3 with our working prototype for Knockout City.

221
00:11:49,815 --> 00:11:52,957
This was 18 months in incubation, we got it to feel really good and

222
00:11:52,997 --> 00:11:53,897
we want to show it to others.

223
00:11:54,878 --> 00:11:57,999
And so many people thanked us for not showing them another Battle Royale.

224
00:11:58,299 --> 00:12:00,661
It was about 50 to 100 other Battle Royales in development.

225
00:12:01,501 --> 00:12:04,622
Because the ones that had been established had quickly gotten to scale.

226
00:12:05,743 --> 00:12:08,945
And the new ones that were coming out were just competing for

227
00:12:09,005 --> 00:12:09,985
diminishing audiences.

228
00:12:11,026 --> 00:12:14,307
Not great barriers to entry once competitors were already at scale.

229
00:12:15,228 --> 00:12:18,170
So think about secret sauce, why is it hard to copy?

230
00:12:18,210 --> 00:12:20,251
But also what the set of capabilities on your team

231
00:12:20,951 --> 00:12:22,032
that makes your team unique

232
00:12:22,092 --> 00:12:24,613
and probably the best to do it as well.

233
00:12:24,653 --> 00:12:26,274
Third principle, is it scalable?

234
00:12:27,255 --> 00:12:29,216
Scalable in a sense of player engagement,

235
00:12:29,496 --> 00:12:32,518
can it engage a player for hours, days, weeks, and months?

236
00:12:33,378 --> 00:12:36,340
And second, can you engage numbers of players?

237
00:12:36,680 --> 00:12:38,681
Can you do hundreds of thousands of users?

238
00:12:39,542 --> 00:12:40,703
Can it go to millions of players?

239
00:12:41,483 --> 00:12:42,524
These tend to be very important

240
00:12:42,564 --> 00:12:44,205
because when you're taking very risky bets.

241
00:12:45,090 --> 00:12:47,712
Hopefully, there are many, many people willing to enjoy it

242
00:12:48,172 --> 00:12:49,253
over long periods of time.

243
00:12:50,854 --> 00:12:52,615
Sometimes takes a while to figure those things out.

244
00:12:54,216 --> 00:12:56,317
So, when we started Valorant Studios,

245
00:12:56,337 --> 00:13:00,239
our initial focus was not about any specific game idea.

246
00:13:00,900 --> 00:13:02,801
It was all about defining what kind of culture

247
00:13:02,881 --> 00:13:04,782
we wanted to cultivate,

248
00:13:04,802 --> 00:13:06,903
the type of team we wanted to assemble.

249
00:13:07,744 --> 00:13:10,085
We really wanted to bring together veteran talent,

250
00:13:10,345 --> 00:13:11,286
as well as new talent,

251
00:13:12,407 --> 00:13:14,468
who are all about going after bold new ideas.

252
00:13:15,390 --> 00:13:18,091
And so that kind of divergent thinking, it starts with the team.

253
00:13:18,891 --> 00:13:24,213
So it's really around building a core team and giving them the room to explore.

254
00:13:25,073 --> 00:13:30,534
Now, it's amazing how we hear all the time that a lot of brilliant, creative,

255
00:13:31,234 --> 00:13:34,975
and technical folks, they weren't given the room to explore.

