00:15:21,503 --> 00:15:28,604
You know, it's really about let's go prototype something and build something and prove whether

277
00:15:28,624 --> 00:15:29,584
something is fun or not.

278
00:15:29,944 --> 00:15:34,865
And it's really sort of investing against the magic that the team finds.

279
00:15:36,446 --> 00:15:41,627
You know, it's the team being really passionate about going after.

280
00:15:42,321 --> 00:15:46,845
you know, specific problems that they're trying to solve. It's finding the magic in these core

281
00:15:46,885 --> 00:15:53,690
interactions that are really novel and unique and different. And you got to build it and iterate on

282
00:15:53,750 --> 00:16:00,175
it until we can put it in the outsider's hands, you know, and subject to a peer review and see

283
00:16:00,275 --> 00:16:06,400
what other people think. And this is, you try and be as rapid as you can. You try and not put a lot

284
00:16:06,440 --> 00:16:07,861
of frills around it. This isn't about.

285
00:16:08,890 --> 00:16:10,771
And unless the game is about an aesthetic

286
00:16:10,811 --> 00:16:12,491
that you're trying to define,

287
00:16:12,531 --> 00:16:13,751
and that's what's unique about it.

288
00:16:14,291 --> 00:16:16,432
You know, if it's about moment to moment mechanics

289
00:16:16,512 --> 00:16:18,292
as an example, you don't need a lot of art.

290
00:16:18,332 --> 00:16:21,332
You kind of focus down on what is really necessary

291
00:16:21,412 --> 00:16:23,993
to prove or disprove a concept.

292
00:16:25,453 --> 00:16:27,574
And you iterate as rapidly as you can.

293
00:16:27,594 --> 00:16:33,054
Now the trick is, and this is challenging,

294
00:16:33,595 --> 00:16:36,075
is that it requires independent funding

